51 PERSONAL PRIVACY PROTECTION
Page 58 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 5.24.(a) Chapter 55A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
2 Article to read:
3 "Article 18.
4 "The Personal Privacy Protection Act.
5 "§ 55A-18-01. Short title.
6 This Article may be cited as The Personal Privacy Protection Act.
7 "§ 55A-18-02. Purpose.
8 This Article prohibits public agencies from collecting, disclosing, or releasing personal
9 information about members, volunteers, and financial and nonfinancial donors to 501(c)
10 nonprofit organizations, except as permitted by State or federal law or regulation. This Article
11 provides penalties for violation of these privacy protections.
12 "§ 55A-18-03. Definitions.
13 In this Article, the following definitions apply:
14 (1) Nonprofit organization. – An entity that (i) is exempt from federal income tax
15 under section 501(c) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 or any successor
16 section, (ii) has submitted an application with the Internal Revenue Service
17 for recognition of an exemption under section 501(c) of the Internal Revenue
18 Code of 1986 or any successor section, or (iii) is a not-for-profit business
19 entity recognized under State law.
20 (2) Person. – As defined in G.S. 12-3.
21 (3) Personal information. – Any list, record, register, registry, roll, roster, or other
22 compilation of data of any kind that directly or indirectly identifies a person
23 as a member, supporter, volunteer, or donor of financial or nonfinancial
24 support to any nonprofit organization. For the purposes of this Article, the
25 terms "supporter" and "volunteer" shall not include members of the governing
26 board, officers, directors, or staff of a nonprofit organization.
27 (4) Public agency. – Any State or local governmental unit and its employees,
28 however designated, including, but not limited to, this State; any department,
29 agency, office, commission, board, division, or other entity of this State,
30 including all boards, departments, and divisions; any political subdivision of
31 this State, including, but not limited to, a county, city, local school
32 administrative unit, community college, or any other local governmental unit,
33 agency, authority, council, board, or commission; or any State or local court,
34 tribunal, or other judicial or quasi-judicial body.
35 "§ 55A-18-04. Protections afforded.
36 (a) Except as provided in G.S. 55A-18-05 of this Article, a public agency shall not do
37 any of the following:
38 (1) Require any person or nonprofit organization to provide the public agency
39 with personal information or otherwise compel the release of personal
40 information.
41 (2) Release, publicize, or otherwise publicly disclose personal information in
42 possession of the public agency.
43 (3) Request or require a current or prospective contractor or grantee with the
44 public agency to provide a list of nonprofit organizations to which the current
45 or prospective contractor or grantee has provided financial or nonfinancial
46 support.
47 (b) Personal information is not a public record under Chapter 132 of the General Statutes.
48 "§ 55A-18-05. Exemptions.
49 This Article does not preclude any of the following:
50 (1) Reporting or disclosure required by Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General
51 Statutes.
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 59

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Issuing of a lawful warrant for personal information by a court of competent
2 jurisdiction.
3 (3) Request for discovery of personal information in litigation if both of the
4 following conditions are met:
5 a. The requestor demonstrates a compelling need for the personal
6 information by clear and convincing evidence.
7 b. The requestor obtains a protective order barring disclosure of personal
8 information to any person not named in the litigation.
9 (4) Admission of personal information as relevant evidence before a court of
10 competent jurisdiction. However, no court shall publicly reveal personal
11 information absent a specific finding of good cause.
12 (5) Releasing personal information by a public agency that was voluntarily
13 released to the public by the person or the nonprofit organization to which it
14 relates.
15 (6) Collection of information disclosing the identity of any director, officer,
16 registered agent, or incorporator of a nonprofit organization in any report or
17 disclosure required by statute to be filed with the Secretary of State. This
18 Article does not preclude an audit, examination, review, or investigation
19 pursuant to the authority of the Secretary of State under Chapters 10B, 55A,
20 78A, 78C, 78D, 120C, or 131F of the General Statutes so long as both of the
21 following apply:
22 a. The personal information is only used in connection with the specific
23 audit, examination, review, or investigation to which the request
24 relates and for any related proceedings.
25 b. Any personal information collected otherwise remains subject to
26 G.S. 55A-18-04(a)(2), unless expressly required by law to be publicly
27 disclosed.
28 (7) Disclosure of personal information derived from a donation to a nonprofit
29 organization that is affiliated with a public agency and required by statute, if
30 the person has not previously requested anonymity from the nonprofit
31 organization.
32 (8) Collection and reporting by a national securities association that is registered
33 pursuant to 15 U.S.C. § 78o-3, any regulations adopted under it, or any
34 information that the national securities association is required to provide
35 pursuant to State law.
36 (9) Requests by the Attorney General for personal information required for an
37 audit, examination, review, or investigation pursuant to Chapters 36C, 36E,
38 55A, 75, and 131F of the General Statutes. Personal information provided
39 pursuant to this exception shall only be used in connection with the specific
40 audit, examination, review, or investigation to which the request relates and
41 for any related proceedings. Any personal information collected shall
42 otherwise remain subject to the provisions of G.S. 55A-18-04(a)(2), unless
43 expressly required by law to be publicly disclosed.
44 "§ 55A-18-06. Penalties.
45 (a) A person alleging a violation of this Article may bring a civil action for appropriate
46 injunctive relief, damages, or both. Damages awarded under this section may include one of the
47 following, as appropriate:
48 (1) A sum of money not less than two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500) to
49 compensate for injury or loss caused by each violation of this Article.
50 (2) For an intentional violation of this Article, a sum of money not to exceed three
51 times the sum described in subdivision (1) of this subsection.
Page 60 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) A court, in rendering a judgment in an action brought under this Article, may award
2 all or a portion of the costs of litigation, including reasonable attorneys' fees and witness fees, to
3 the complainant in the action if the court determines that the award is appropriate.
4 (c) A person who knowingly violates this Article is guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor.
5 "§ 55A-18-07. Severability.
6 If any provision of this Article or its application to any person or circumstance is held invalid,
7 then the invalidity shall not affect other provisions or applications of this Article that can be given
8 effect without the invalid provision or application and, to that end, the provisions of this Article
9 shall be severable."
