18 "§ 115D-30.20. Gateway to College Program.
19 The purpose of the first semester of the Gateway to College Program is to address additional
20 support to successfully complete the Program. Students may need to take developmental courses
21 necessary for the transition to more challenging courses; therefore, the State Board of Community
22 Colleges shall (i) permit high school students who are enrolled in Gateway to College Programs
23 to enroll in developmental courses based on an assessment of their individual student needs by a
24 high school and community college staff team and (ii) include this coursework in computing the
25 budget FTE for the colleges.
26 "§ 115D-30.25. NC Career Coach Program.
27 (a) Purpose. – There is established the NC Career Coach Program to place community
28 college career coaches in high schools to assist students with determining career goals and
29 identifying community college programs that would enable students to achieve these goals.
30 (b) Memorandum of Understanding. – The board of trustees of a community college and
31 a local board of education of a local school administrative unit within the service area of the
32 community college shall enter into a memorandum of understanding for the placement of career
33 coaches employed by the board of trustees of the community college in schools within the local
34 school administrative unit. At a minimum, the memorandum of understanding shall include the
35 following:
36 (1) Requirement that the community college provides the following:
37 a. Hiring, training, and supervision of career coaches. The board of
38 trustees may include a local board of education liaison on the hiring
39 committee to participate in the decision making regarding hiring for
40 the coach positions.
41 b. Salary, benefits, and all other expenses related to the employment of
42 the career coach. The coach will be an employee of the board of
43 trustees and will not be an agent or employee of the local board of
44 education.
45 c. Development of pedagogical materials and technologies needed to
46 enhance the advising process.
47 d. Criminal background checks required by the local school
48 administrative unit for employees working directly with students.
49 e. Agreement that, while on any school campus, the career coach will
50 obey all local board of education rules and will be subject to the
51 authority of the school building administration.
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 89

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Requirement that the local school administrative unit provides the following
2 to career coaches:
3 a. Access to student records, as needed to carry out the coach's job
4 responsibilities.
5 b. Office space on site appropriate for student advising.
6 c. Information technology resources, including, but not limited to,
7 internet access, telephone, and copying.
8 d. Initial school orientation and ongoing integration into the faculty and
9 staff community.
10 e. Promotion of school-wide awareness of coach duties.
11 f. Facilitation of the coach's access to individual classes and larger
12 assemblies for the purposes of awareness building.
13 (c) Application for NC Career Coach Program Funding. – The board of trustees of a
14 community college and a local board of education of a local school administrative unit within the
15 service area of the community college jointly may apply for available funds for NC Career Coach
16 Program funding from the State Board of Community Colleges. The State Board of Community
17 Colleges shall establish a process for award of funds as follows:
18 (1) Advisory committee. – Establishment of an advisory committee, which shall
19 include representatives from the NC Community College System, the
20 Department of Public Instruction, the Department of Commerce, and at least
21 three representatives of the business community, to review applications and
22 make recommendations for funding awards to the State Board.
23 (2) Application submission requirements. – The State Board of Community
24 Colleges shall require at least the following:
25 a. Evidence of a signed memorandum of understanding that meets, at a
26 minimum, the requirements of this section.
27 b. Evidence that the funding request will be matched with local funds in
28 accordance with the following:
29 1. Matching funds may come from public or private sources.
30 2. The match amount shall be determined based on the
31 development tier designation of the county in which the local
32 school administrative unit is located where the career coach is
33 assigned on the date of the award of funds by the State Board
34 of Community Colleges according to the following:
35 I. If located in a tier one county as defined in
36 G.S. 143B-437.08, no local match shall be required.
37 II. If located in a tier two county as defined in
38 G.S. 143B-437.08, one dollar ($1.00) of local funds for
39 every two dollars ($2.00) in State funds shall be
40 required.
41 III. If located in a tier three county as defined in
42 G.S. 143B-437.08, one dollar ($1.00) of local funds for
43 every one dollar ($1.00) in State funds shall be
44 required.
45 (3) Awards criteria. – The State Board of Community Colleges shall develop
46 criteria for consideration in determining the award of funds that shall include
47 the following:
48 a. Consideration of the workforce needs of business and industry in the
49 region.
50 b. Targeting of resources to enhance ongoing economic activity within
51 the community college service area and surrounding counties.
