16 SECTION 7.14.(a) Part 3A of Article 8 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is
17 amended by adding new sections to read:
18 "§ 115C-102.10. Technology costs considerations.
19 The State Board of Education shall adopt rules requiring all public school units to evaluate
20 the following when acquiring technology, computer hardware, and software:
21 (1) The long-term cost of ownership, including costs of repairing the technology,
22 computer hardware, or software.
23 (2) Any flexibility for innovation during the life of the technology, computer
24 hardware, or software.
25 (3) Any anticipated resale or salvage value at the end of the target life cycle for
26 the technology, computer hardware, or software based on the average resale
27 or salvage value of similar technology, computer hardware, or software as a
28 percentage of the initial cost of purchase.
29 "§ 115C-102.11 Break/fix rate reporting requirement.
30 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
31 (1) Break/fix rate. – The percentage obtained by dividing the number of school
32 technology devices reported as malfunctioning or needing repair due to
33 physical damage, hardware failure, or other breakage incidents prior to the
34 stated life cycle period, not covered by insurance or a policy plan period, by
35 the total number of school technology devices in operation during that period.
36 (2) School technology device. – Any electronic or computerized equipment
37 provided for educational purposes in a public school unit, including
38 computers, tablets, interactive whiteboards, and similar devices or anything
39 considered a digital device for purposes of the digital learning dashboard
40 pursuant to G.S. 115C-102.9.
41 (b) Each governing body of a public school unit shall submit a report on the following
42 information to the State Board of Education by August 15 annually:
43 (1) The break/fix rate of the school technology devices in the public school unit
44 for the previous school year.
45 (2) The total number of school technology devices currently in operation in the
46 public school unit.
47 (3) The total number of school technology devices in the public school unit
48 requiring repair that (i) underwent repair or (ii) were no longer in service
49 during the previous school year.
50 (4) The total amount of funds spent to repair or replace school technology devices
51 during the previous school year.
