Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 119

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 7.28. G.S. 115C-377 reads as rewritten:
2 "§ 115C-377. Feminine Hygiene Products Grant Program.
3 (a) Program; Purpose. – The Department of Public Instruction shall establish the
4 Feminine Hygiene Products Grant Program (Program) to assist public school units participating
5 in the Program in providing provide students with feminine hygiene products at no charge to the
6 student. The Department shall run the Program in accordance with this section in each year in
7 which funds are made available for the purpose.
8 (b) Grants. – To the extent funds are made available for the Program, the Department of
9 Public Instruction shall award public school units grants of up to five thousand dollars ($5,000)
10 on a first-come, first-served basis, and the Department shall prioritize awarding grants to public
11 school units that did not receive an award pursuant to the Program in the previous fiscal year. No
12 public school unit shall receive more than one grant per fiscal year.
13 (b1) Participation. – The Department of Public Instruction shall develop a process through
14 which public school units can elect to participate in the Program for each school year.
15 (b2) Contract for Products. – The Department of Public Instruction shall contract with the
16 Diaper Bank of North Carolina to provide feminine hygiene products to all public school units
17 that elect to participate in the Program on a pro rata basis based on the number of female students
18 in grades six through 12 in the participating public school unit.
19 (c) Reporting. – No later than March 15, 2023, and every year thereafter that funds are
20 made available for 15 of each year of the Program, the Department shall report to the Joint
21 Legislative Education Oversight Committee on the public school units receiving grants products
22 under the Program, the specific number of feminine hygiene products purchased with the grant
23 funds, provided through the Program, the number of students served by the Program, and the
24 impact of the Program on student health and well-being."
