20 CAREER DEVELOPMENT ADJUSTMENT
21 SECTION 7.45.(a) Pilot Program Established; Purpose. – The Superintendent of
22 Public Instruction shall create an Annual Career Development Plan Pilot Program (Program) for
23 students entering the seventh grade at select schools during the 2025-2026 and 2026-2027 school
24 years and continuing through the students' graduation from high school. The purpose of the
25 Program shall be to evaluate the efficacy of reviewing Career Development Plans (Plans)
26 annually to better align students for on-time graduation and achievement of college and career
27 goals and to ensure that all students graduate from high school college or career ready.
28 SECTION 7.45.(b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply to this section:
29 (1) Career Development Plan. – An individual plan created by each student that
30 establishes the student's plan throughout middle and high school for
31 graduation and career development pursuant to G.S. 115C-158.10.
32 (2) Local board of education. – A local board of education governing a partnered
33 school.
34 (3) Parent. – Defined in G.S. 115C-76.1.
35 (4) Partnered school. – A middle school and high school governed by a local
36 board of education where at least half of the student population of the middle
37 school is assigned to attend the associated high school.
38 SECTION 7.45.(c) Partnered Schools. – The Superintendent shall select 12
39 partnered schools that are proportionally representative of the population size and geographic
40 distribution of public high schools in the State. The Superintendent shall provide a process for
41 schools to apply to participate in the Program as partnered schools. The Superintendent shall be
42 responsible for the final selection of partnered schools. In the event that there are fewer than 12
43 applicants, the Superintendent shall collaborate with local superintendents to select schools to be
44 partnered schools. Partnered schools shall have each student entering the seventh grade during
45 the 2025-2026 and 2026-2027 school years complete an annual review of Plans.
46 SECTION 7.45.(d) Local Board of Education and IEP Support. – The local board
47 of education shall ensure that students in partnered schools are provided assistance by a school
48 counselor and planning time during the instructional day each school year to update their Plans.
49 For students with disabilities, the student's IEP team, if applicable, may assist the student in
50 completing and updating the Plan. Updates to Plans shall be made prior to student scheduling of
51 courses for the next school year.
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 133

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 7.45.(e) Parental Involvement. – Partnered schools shall encourage
2 parents to participate in development of Plans with their students and to sign a form provided by
3 the school acknowledging the annual revisions of the Plans. Local boards of education shall
4 ensure that Plans are easily accessible to students and parents and shall provide parents annual
5 written notice of the creation or revision of a Plan, information on how to access the Plan, a
6 listing of course offerings for the next school year with a description of the content of each course,
7 and high school graduation requirements where appropriate. Prior to creating or updating a
8 student's Plan, a school counselor shall attempt to meet with the student's parent, either in person
9 or virtually, to explain the possible effects that the Plan might have on the student's graduation
10 requirements and career development planning. Beginning in the tenth grade and continuing
11 throughout the student's high school enrollment, a school counselor shall provide each student
12 and parent information regarding State and federal need-based and merit-based financial aid
13 programs to support postsecondary education and training using information provided by the
14 State Education Assistance Authority and College Foundation of North Carolina. The school
15 counselor shall also provide information on the free application for federal student aid (FAFSA),
16 its use, and notify the parent that information included in the FAFSA is confidential and not
17 accessible by the school.
18 SECTION 7.45.(f) Initial Career Development Plans. – Students in seventh grade in
19 partnered schools shall develop an initial career development plan which will provide guidance
20 as students develop Plans.
21 SECTION 7.45.(g) Annual Career Development Plan Updates. – In partnered
22 schools, Plans shall be updated annually in addition to the following information being provided
23 to students:
24 (1) For eighth grade students, by the end of the school year, a list of the required
25 core courses to be taken in ninth and tenth grades.
26 (2) For tenth grade students, an identification of the graduation requirements
27 relevant to the student's chosen postsecondary goals based on the student's
28 career development planning.
29 (3) For eleventh grade students not meeting the career and college readiness
30 standards established by the State Board of Community Colleges, a plan for
31 enrolling in remedial coursework for his or her senior year.
32 (4) Any other minimum requirements established by the Superintendent.
33 SECTION 7.45.(h) Reporting Requirement. – The Superintendent or a local board
34 of education shall develop reporting requirements for partnered schools participating in the
35 Program to provide information on the effectiveness of the annual review of the Plans. The
36 Superintendent shall report to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee by August
37 15, 2026, and each year thereafter on the progress of the Program, including any logistical issues
38 that have arisen with the Program.
