14 RESPONSIBLE FATHERHOOD NORTH CAROLINA ACT
15 SECTION 7.53.(a) The General Assembly recognizes that families are stronger
16 when both parents act responsibly in caring for their children. It is the intent of the General
17 Assembly to recognize and support the important and unique role that fathers play in ensuring
18 the physical, emotional, and economic well-being of their children and families.
19 SECTION 7.53.(b) The Department shall contract for the development and
20 implementation of the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program. The program shall
21 provide an opportunity for every father in the State to be able to obtain information and
22 inspiration that will motivate and enable him to enhance his abilities as a father, recognizing that
23 some fathers have greater challenges than others and would benefit from greater support. The
24 entity the Department contracts with to develop, implement, and manage the program, "Program
25 Manager," shall be a nonprofit organization that satisfies all of the following criteria:
26 (1) Has a history of focusing on responsible fatherhood, including providing
27 online resources to fathers, and engaging fathers, father figures, and children
28 through community-based and school-based events to encourage responsible
29 fatherhood.
30 (2) Has the organizational capacity to manage a statewide initiative and
31 successfully carry out the requirements of this section.
32 SECTION 7.53.(c) The Program Manager shall be solely responsible for developing,
33 implementing, and managing the program which shall include at least the following:
34 (1) A statewide media campaign that increases the awareness and importance of
35 fathers being involved in their children's lives.
36 (2) Resources and information for fathers and father figures to increase
37 engagement and involvement in their children's lives.
38 (3) Promotion of related fatherhood programs that are provided by the
39 Department of Public Instruction, the Community College System, or The
40 University of North Carolina System.
41 SECTION 7.53.(d) To most effectively use the funds appropriated to this program,
42 the Program Manager shall identify and use other existing media assets, content, and online
43 resources it deems appropriate, including any existing media assets, content, and online resources
44 it has available, to implement and execute the items required by this section.
45 SECTION 7.53.(e) The Program Manager shall administer a grant program to award
46 grants to nonprofit community-based organizations that address the needs of fathers in
47 accordance with the following:
48 (1) The Program Manager shall award the following types of grants:
49 a. Grants that comprehensively address the needs of fathers, such as
50 assisting them in finding employment, managing child support
51 obligations, transitioning from a period of incarceration, accessing
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 151

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 health care, understanding child development, and enhancing
2 parenting skills. Services provided shall be tailored to the needs of the
3 father being served. Case management services shall be provided to
4 the fathers who are served by the grants under this subdivision.
5 b. Grants that provide evidence-based parenting education specifically
6 for fathers. The grants under this subdivision do not require case
7 management services.
8 (2) The Program Manager shall prioritize awarding grants according to the
9 following:
10 a. Need in a geographic area and the population to be served by the grant
11 as indicated by, at a minimum, all of the following:
12 1. Unemployment rates.
13 2. Incarceration rates.
14 3. Housing instability.
15 4. The number of single-parent households.
16 5. The number of public benefit recipients.
17 6. Graduation rates.
18 7. Levels of academic achievement.
19 b. If an applicant has a primary mission of, or a history of a significant
20 focus on and effective work toward, addressing the needs of men in
21 their role as fathers.
22 c. Applicant current and historical involvement in the community being
23 served.
24 d. Applicant commitment and capability to employ competent staff who
25 can effectively engage with the fathers being served, including, at a
26 minimum, those individuals who share a similar background as the
27 fathers being served.
28 e. The number of individuals the applicant plans to serve through the
29 grant and the projected costs for the program.
30 f. Applicant organizational capacity to effectively meet the requirements
31 of the grant and to deliver the programs proposed by the applicant. The
32 Program Manager may offer technical assistance to applicants and
33 grant recipients that have lower organizational capacity as long as such
34 organizations have, or the organization's leadership has, significant
35 experience serving fathers.
36 (3) Grant recipients shall submit reports to the Department in a format and at
37 intervals prescribed by the Department.
38 SECTION 7.53.(f) Of the funds appropriated to the Department of Public Instruction
39 in this act for the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program, the Department shall use up
40 to two million dollars ($2,000,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to
41 contract for the Program Manager as required in subsection (b) of this section. The remainder of
42 the funds shall be used for the grants authorized in subsection (e) of this section.
43
44 COMPETITIVE SPEECH AND DEBATE GRANT PILOT
45 SECTION 7.54.(a) Program; Purpose. – To the extent funds are made available for
46 the purpose, there is established the Competitive Speech and Debate Team Grant Pilot Program
47 (Program). The purpose of the Program is to allow each public school serving students in grades
48 nine through 12 in North Carolina to form a speech and debate team and to allow the team to
49 participate in speech and debate competitions. The Program shall begin in the 2025-2026 school
50 year and conclude at the end of the 2028-2029 school year.
Page 152 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 7.54.(b) Eligibility. – Any public school unit that includes a school that
2 serves students in grades nine through 12 is eligible to apply to the Department of Public
3 Instruction for a grant to develop, maintain, or expand an educational and competitive speech
4 and debate team.
5 SECTION 7.54.(c) Applications; Criteria and Guidelines. – No later than August 1
6 of each year that funds are made available for the Program, the Department shall develop and
7 publish criteria and guidelines for the application process for the Program in the upcoming school
8 year. The Department shall accept applications until September 30 of each school year.
9 Applications shall include, at a minimum, a proposed budget for the speech and debate team.
10 SECTION 7.54.(d) Award; Use of Funds. – The Department shall award grants to
11 selected applicants by October 31 of each year that funds are made available for the Program.
12 The Department shall determine the amount of each award up to a maximum of ten thousand
13 dollars ($10,000) per team per school year and may only include two stipends, one lead team
14 coach stipend of up to two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500) and one assistant team coach
15 stipend of one thousand five hundred dollars ($1,500). Funds may be used for any of the
16 following purposes:
17 (1) Provide stipends for coaches.
18 (2) Make payments associated with participation in a speech and debate league or
19 competition.
20 (3) Travel to and from speech and debate competitions.
21 SECTION 7.54.(e) Speech and debate teams receiving funds through the Program
22 shall participate in the Tarheel Forensic League and the National Speech and Debate Association.
23 SECTION 7.54.(f) Student Participation. – If a student is enrolled in a school that
24 does not offer a speech and debate team, the student is eligible to participate on the speech and
25 debate team at the school located geographically closest to where the student resides that does
26 have a team. A student joining a team under the authority of this section shall be responsible for
27 transportation to and from the school where the team meets. Nothing in this section prohibits a
28 school from enforcing guidelines for student participation in extracurricular activities, such as
29 academic performance requirements, nor does it prohibit a speech and debate team from
30 conducting a selection process for the team, so long as the student is able to participate in the
31 selection process as if the student were enrolled in that school.
32 SECTION 7.54.(g) Reporting. – No later than February 15 of each school year in
33 which funds are made available for the Program, the Department shall report the following
34 information to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research
35 Division:
36 (1) The public school units receiving grants and the amount of the grant.
37 (2) A description of how the grants were used.
38 (3) The public school units that applied for grants but did not receive one.
39 (4) The extent to which students participating in speech and debate programs
40 funded by the Program experienced measurable improvement in academic
41 performance.
42 SECTION 7.54.(h) Of the funds appropriated to the Department of Public
43 Instruction in this act, the Department shall use the sum of five hundred thousand dollars
44 ($500,000) in recurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to establish and administer the
45 Competitive Speech and Debate Team Grant Pilot Program, as established by this section. At the
46 conclusion of the Program, when creating the base budget for the 2029-2031 fiscal biennium, the
47 Director of the Budget shall not include these funds for the 2029-2030 fiscal year.
