9 "§ 116-209.114. Scholarship.
10 (a) Scholarship Benefits. – To the extent funds are made available for this purpose,
11 scholarship granted pursuant to this Part shall consist of the following benefits and other
12 requirements and limitations for eligible children enrolled as undergraduate students at eligible
13 institutions:
14 (1) Scholarship funds may be used for any of the following purposes:
15 a. The cost of attendance at an eligible institution, including tuition, fees,
16 room, and board.
17 b. The cost of short-term workforce training courses leading to industry
18 credentials.
19 (2) An eligible child may only receive scholarship funds for a total of four
20 academic years. The eligible child is not required to be continuously enrolled
21 to receive subsequent awards in a term, quarter, or semester. However, the
22 eligible child shall not receive an award after the end of a six-year period
23 beginning on the date a scholarship is first awarded. Whenever an eligible
24 child is enrolled in an eligible institution and the period for a scholarship ends
25 while enrolled in a term, quarter, or semester, such period shall be extended
26 to the end of such term, quarter, or semester, but not beyond the eligibility
27 limitation of four academic years.
28 (3) No scholarship awarded to an eligible child pursuant to this Part shall exceed
29 an amount equal to the highest cost of attendance for attendance at a State
30 educational institution for that academic year.
31 (4) As necessary, the Authority shall reduce a scholarship provided pursuant to
32 this Part so that the sum of all grants and scholarship aid covering the cost of
33 attendance received by the student, including the scholarship under this
34 section, shall not exceed the cost of attendance for the eligible institution at
35 which the student is enrolled.
36 (5) A student who has been awarded a scholarship under this section shall
37 maintain satisfactory academic progress according to the standards of the
38 eligible institution throughout the four academic years for which the student
39 is eligible for a scholarship under this section.
40 (b) Selection of Recipients. – The Authority shall select recipients for scholarships and
41 disburse the scholarships in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 116-209.116. The Authority
42 may contract with another State agency or a third-party entity to determine eligibility and select
43 recipients as required by G.S. 116-209.116(a)(1). In the event there are not sufficient funds to
44 provide each eligible child who has properly applied with a full scholarship as provided by this
45 Part, the Authority shall determine the necessary adjustment of awards consistent with the
46 priority requirements set forth in subsection (c) of this section, including establishing a lottery,
47 awarding scholarships on a pro rata share basis, or both, for the academic year.
48 (c) Award of Funds; Priority. – Beginning May 1 of the year in which the recipient enrolls
49 in an eligible institution, the Authority shall award scholarship funds to students who have
50 properly applied and are otherwise eligible under the Program in the following order:
Page 214 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Students who received scholarship funds under Part 2 of Article 14 of Chapter
2 143B of the General Statutes in the previous academic year.
3 (2) Students who received scholarship funds under Part 2 of Article 14 of Chapter
4 143B of the General Statutes in any previous academic year.
5 (3) All other students.
6 "§ 116-209.116. Administration and funding.
7 (a) Responsibilities of the Authority. – The Authority shall administer the award of
8 scholarships under this Part and have all of the following associated responsibilities:
9 (1) Determining the eligibility of applicants and selecting recipients.
10 (2) Awarding funds to scholarship recipients.
11 (3) Suspending or revoking scholarships if the Authority is notified and finds that
12 a recipient does any of the following:
13 a. Fails to maintain satisfactory academic progress.
14 b. Engages in riots, unlawful demonstrations, the seizure of educational
15 buildings, or otherwise engages in disorderly conduct, breaches of the
16 peace, or unlawful assemblies.
17 (4) Promulgating such rules and regulations not inconsistent with the other
18 provisions of this Part as the Authority deems necessary for the orderly
19 administration of the Program. These rules may require eligible institutions to
20 provide such reports and other information as are necessary to carry out the
21 provisions of this Part, including whether a recipient is failing to maintain
22 satisfactory academic progress or engaging in any of the actions described in
23 sub-subdivision b. of subdivision (3) of this subsection.
24 (b) Funding. – Funds for the support of the Program shall be appropriated to the Board
25 of Governors of The University of North Carolina to be allocated to the Authority as a reserve
26 for payment of approved expenses for the cost of attendance. Funds to support the Program shall
27 be supported by receipts from the Escheat Fund, as provided by G.S. 116B-7, to the extent those
28 funds are used for worthy and needy residents of this State who are enrolled in public institutions
29 of higher education of this State.
30 (c) Withdrawal from Enrollment. – Irrespective of any other provision of this Part, the
31 Authority may prescribe special procedures for adjusting the accounts of scholarship recipients
32 who, for reasons of illness, physical inability to attend class, or for other valid reason satisfactory
33 to the Authority may withdraw from eligible institutions prior to the completion of the term,
