39 CHILD CARE WORKFORCE PILOT PROGRAM
40 SECTION 9D.11.(a) Of the funds appropriated in this act to the Department of
41 Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, the sum of
42 one million four hundred seventy-six thousand dollars ($1,476,000) in nonrecurring funds for the
43 2025-2026 fiscal year shall be allocated to the North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., to
44 provide the State match for implementing the pilot program described in this section as follows:
45 (1) The sum of nine hundred seventy-two thousand dollars ($972,000) for the
46 2025-2026 fiscal year for the State portion of tuition costs.
47 (2) The sum of five hundred four thousand dollars ($504,000) for the 2025-2026
48 fiscal year for the stipends provided with State funds in accordance with
49 subsection (f) of this section.
50 SECTION 9D.11.(b) Funds described in subsection (a) of this section shall be
51 allocated equally among the local partnerships selected to participate in the pilot program. Local
Page 246 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 partnerships shall provide documentation of a twenty-five percent (25%) local match as a
2 condition of receiving State funds. Any unexpended and unencumbered funds at the end of the
3 fiscal year from the funds provided under this section shall not revert to the General Fund but
4 shall remain available for use in accordance with this section. Funds provided under this section
5 shall not be used for administrative costs.
6 SECTION 9D.11.(c) The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., in
7 collaboration with the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office, shall develop and
8 implement a two-year pilot program that expands the child care workforce academies currently
9 operating in Johnston and Wayne Counties. The pilot program shall establish child care
10 workforce academies across the State designed to provide free, comprehensive training and
11 support to individuals, with no experience or education in child care, who are interested in
12 pursuing a career in child care.
13 SECTION 9D.11.(d) Local partnerships in the following counties shall participate
14 in the pilot program described under this section: Johnston and Wayne. The North Carolina
15 Partnership for Children, Inc., (NCPC), in collaboration with the Community Colleges System
16 Office, shall select 10 additional local partnerships to participate in the pilot program from the
17 four local partnership regions of the statewide NCPC network, which regions are the West,
18 Mid-West, Mid-East, and East.
19 SECTION 9D.11.(e) The Community Colleges System Office and local community
20 colleges shall coordinate to ensure that graduates of the child care workforce academies meet all
21 requirements to be credentialed with the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential as lead
22 teachers in child care in this State.
23 SECTION 9D.11.(f) Each child care workforce academy (academy) shall seek to
24 enroll no less than 10 students, with a goal of enrolling 15 students in each course. The academy
25 shall operate up to eight hours per day over a two- to three-week period. A participating
26 community college shall strive to offer an academy up to three times per year, with at least one
27 of the three academies occurring at the end of the traditional public school calendar year to allow
28 participation by interested high school and college students. The academy shall be offered
29 free-of-charge to applicants. Students participating in the academy shall receive the knowledge,
30 skills, and training, including the necessary health screenings, background checks, and
31 fingerprinting, required for employment as a lead teacher in a licensed child care program in this
32 State. Upon successful completion of the academy, each student shall receive a North Carolina
33 Early Childhood Credential that will enable the student to begin teaching in a licensed child care
34 program immediately upon graduation. A local partnership may provide each graduate with a
35 one-time stipend. If a one-time stipend for completing the course is provided, the amount shall
36 be at the discretion of the local partnership but shall not be less than one hundred fifty dollars
37 ($150.00). Students shall be eligible to receive an additional one-time stipend in the amount of
38 five hundred dollars ($500.00) in State funds after completing one year of employment as a lead
39 teacher in a licensed child care program in this State.
40 SECTION 9D.11.(g) The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., and local
41 partnerships shall (i) collaborate with the community college in the county or counties in which
42 the local partnership is located, as practicable, to implement the child care workforce academy
43 and (ii) ensure information about the child care workforce academy in the respective county is
44 made available to the public.
45 SECTION 9D.11.(h) The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., (NCPC), in
46 collaboration with the local partnerships and community colleges participating in the pilot
47 program, shall submit a progress report on the pilot program to the Joint Legislative Oversight
48 Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division by March 31, 2026,
49 with any concerns or recommendations for program expansion. A final report shall be submitted
50 by December 31, 2026, and shall include, at a minimum, the following:
