2 rare disease patient organization, shall serve more than three consecutive terms. The initial
3 physician members and the initial member representing a rare disease patient organization may
4 serve for up to four consecutive terms. Thereafter, members appointed by the President Pro
5 Tempore of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, and the Governor shall
6 serve for a term of two years; and members appointed by the Secretary shall serve for a term of
7 two, three, or four years, as determined by the chair of the advisory council.
8 (c1) Vacancies and Removals. – Any appointment to fill a vacancy on the advisory council
9 created by the resignation, dismissal, death, or disability of a member shall be filled by the
10 appointing authority for the balance of the unexpired term. Each appointing authority may
11 remove any member appointed by that appointing authority for misfeasance, malfeasance, or
12 nonfeasance.
13 (d) Per Diem and Expenses. – Members of the advisory council shall receive per diem
14 and necessary travel and subsistence expenses in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 138-5
15 or G.S. 138-6 or travel and subsistence expenses in accordance with the provisions of
16 G.S. 120-3.1, as applicable.
17 (e) Administrative Support. – All administrative support and other services required by
18 the advisory council shall be provided by the School of Medicine of the University of North
19 Carolina at Chapel Hill.Department.
20 (f) Upon the recommendation of the Dean of the School of Medicine of the University
21 of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Selection of Chair. – The Secretary shall select the chair of the
22 advisory council from among the members of the council. The chair shall serve in this position
23 until the expiration of his or her term.
24 (g) The chair shall convene the first meeting of the advisory council no later than October
25 1, 2015. Meetings and Quorum. – A majority of the council members shall constitute a quorum.
26 A majority vote of a quorum shall be required for any official action of the advisory council.
27 Following the first meeting, the advisory council shall meet at least quarterly. The advisory
28 council may meet more frequently upon the call of the chair or upon the request of a majority of
29 council members.
30 "§ 130A-33.66. Advisory Council on Rare Diseases; powers and duties; reports.
31 The advisory council shall have the following powers and duties:
32 (1) Advise on coordinating the Governor, the Secretary, and the General
33 Assembly on all of the following:
34 a. Coordination of statewide efforts for the to study of the incidence of
35 rare diseases within the State and the status of the rare disease
36 community.
37 b. Coordination of statewide efforts to increase public awareness and
38 understanding of rare diseases.
39 c. Identification of policy issues related to rare diseases and the
40 advancement of policy initiatives related to rare diseases at the State
41 and federal levels.
42 d. The appropriation of State funds to facilitate increased public
43 awareness of and improved treatment for rare diseases.
44 (2) Report to the Secretary, the Governor, and the Joint Legislative Oversight
45 Committee on Health and Human Services Services, and the Fiscal Research
46 Division on behalf of the General Assembly not later than January 1, 2016,
47 and annually thereafter, on the activities of the advisory council and its
48 findings and recommendations regarding rare disease research and care in
49 North Carolina, including any recommendations for statutory changes and
50 amendments to the structure, organization, and powers or duties of the
51 advisory council.
