1 INTENSIVE FAMILY PRESERVATION SERVICES FUNDING, PERFORMANCE
2 ENHANCEMENTS, AND REPORT
3 SECTION 9J.2.(a) Notwithstanding the provisions of G.S. 143B-150.6, the
4 Intensive Family Preservation Services (IFPS) Program shall provide intensive services to
5 children and families in cases of abuse, neglect, and dependency where a child is at imminent
6 risk of removal from the home and to children and families in cases of abuse where a child is not
7 at imminent risk of removal. The IFPS shall be implemented statewide on a regional basis. The
8 IFPS shall ensure the application of standardized assessment criteria for determining imminent
9 risk and clear criteria for determining out-of-home placement.
10 SECTION 9J.2.(b) The Department of Health and Human Services shall require that
11 any program or entity that receives State, federal, or other funding for the purpose of IFPS shall
12 provide information and data that allows for the following:
13 (1) An established follow-up system with a minimum of six months of follow-up
14 services.
15 (2) Detailed information on the specific interventions applied, including
16 utilization indicators and performance measurements.
17 (3) Cost-benefit data.
18 (4) Data on long-term benefits associated with IFPS. This data shall be obtained
19 by tracking families through the intervention process.
20 (5) The number of families remaining intact and the associated interventions
21 while in IFPS and 12 months thereafter.
22 (6) The number and percentage, by race, of children who received IFPS compared
23 to the ratio of their distribution in the general population involved with Child
24 Protective Services.
25 SECTION 9J.2.(c) The Department shall continue implementing a
26 performance-based funding protocol and shall only provide funding to those programs and
27 entities providing the required information specified in subsection (b) of this section. The amount
28 of funding shall be based on the individual performance of each program.
29 SECTION 9J.2.(d) The Department shall submit an annual report to the Joint
30 Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research
31 Division by December 1 of each year that provides the information and data collected pursuant
32 to subsection (b) of this section.
