34 FEDERAL CHILD SUPPORT INCENTIVE PAYMENTS
35 SECTION 9J.6.(a) Centralized Services. – The North Carolina Child Support
36 Services (NCCSS) Section of the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Social
37 Services, shall retain up to fifteen percent (15%) of the annual federal incentive payments it
38 receives from the federal government to enhance centralized child support services. To
39 accomplish this requirement, NCCSS shall do the following:
40 (1) In consultation with representatives from county child support services
41 programs, identify how federal incentive funding could improve centralized
42 services.
43 (2) Use federal incentive funds to improve the effectiveness of the State's
44 centralized child support services by supplementing and not supplanting State
45 expenditures for those services.
46 (3) Continue to develop and implement rules that explain the State process for
47 calculating and distributing federal incentive funding to county child support
48 services programs.
49 SECTION 9J.6.(b) County Child Support Services Programs. – NCCSS shall
50 allocate no less than eighty-five percent (85%) of the annual federal incentive payments it
51 receives from the federal government to county child support services programs to improve
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 281

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 effectiveness and efficiency using the federal performance measures. To that end, NCCSS shall
2 do the following:
3 (1) In consultation with representatives from county child support services
4 programs, examine the current methodology for distributing federal incentive
5 funding to the county programs and determine whether an alternative formula
6 would be appropriate. NCCSS shall use its current formula for distributing
7 federal incentive funding until an alternative formula is adopted.
8 (2) Upon adopting an alternative formula, develop a process to phase in the
9 alternative formula for distributing federal incentive funding over a four-year
10 period.
11 SECTION 9J.6.(c) Reporting by County Child Support Services Programs. –
12 NCCSS shall continue implementing guidelines that identify appropriate uses for federal
13 incentive funding. To ensure those guidelines are properly followed, NCCSS shall require county
14 child support services programs to comply with each of the following:
15 (1) Submit an annual plan describing how federal incentive funding would
16 improve program effectiveness and efficiency as a condition of receiving
17 federal incentive funding.
18 (2) Report annually on the following: (i) how federal incentive funding has
19 improved program effectiveness and efficiency and been reinvested into their
20 programs, (ii) documentation that the funds were spent according to their
21 annual plans, and (iii) any deviations from their plans.
22 SECTION 9J.6.(d) Reporting by NCCSS. – NCCSS shall submit a report on federal
23 child support incentive funding to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and
24 Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division by November 1 of each year. The report shall
25 describe how federal incentive funds enhanced centralized child support services to benefit
26 county child support services programs and improved the effectiveness and efficiency of county
27 child support services programs. The report shall further include any changes to the State process
28 that NCCSS used in calculating and distributing federal incentive funding to county child support
29 services programs and any recommendations for further changes.
