45 CHILD CARE HOME DIRECT SUPPORT PILOT
46 SECTION 9M.2.(a) Of the funds appropriated in this act from the federal Child Care
47 and Development Block Grant under Section 9M.1 of this act to the Department of Health and
48 Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, for quality and
49 availability initiatives, the sum of three million five hundred thousand dollars ($3,500,000) for
50 each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium shall be allocated in equal amounts to three councils
51 of governments, one of which is in a county from the Coastal Plain Region, one of which is in a
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 299

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 county from the Mountain Region, and one of which is in a county from the Piedmont Region,
2 as those regions are defined in G.S. 143B-1373(a). These funds shall be used to establish a
3 two-year pilot program coordinated by those councils of governments to build child care capacity
4 in those counties. Each designated council of governments shall issue a request for application
5 (RFA) for a vendor to contract with the respective council of governments to administer the pilot
6 program, and each vendor selected shall have experience providing support and assistance to
7 early child care providers. To receive funds, the vendor shall partner with the councils of
8 governments in the respective county to (i) increase the supply of child care programs by
9 recruiting and coaching prospective child care providers through the initial business planning and
10 implementation process and (ii) ensure sustainability by executing a two-year mentorship
11 program for the new child care programs created pursuant to this section.
12 SECTION 9M.2.(b) The councils of governments participating in the pilot program
13 may use (i) a portion of these funds for additional solutions provided by the vendor within the
14 early childhood education space to meet localized needs and in support of recovery,
15 rehabilitation, and ongoing needs of their member communities and (ii) up to five percent (5%)
16 of the funds allocated to the respective councils of governments under this act for administrative
17 costs.
18 SECTION 9M.2.(c) The councils of governments participating in the pilot program
19 shall select a vendor that has all of the following qualifications:
20 (1) Experience and active or successful contracts to establish new family child
21 care homes in at least three other states.
22 (2) Technology to operate a substitute teacher pool that matches teachers with
23 providers and facilitates payments and quality control, and experience in
24 creating an active substitute teacher pool in one state.
25 (3) Experience successfully establishing family child care homes in rural
26 communities and addressing child care access in underserved areas.
27 (4) Technology that (i) allows for the recruitment of child care providers via
28 microsites, (ii) allows the onboarding of child care providers via a licensing
29 checklist, (iii) allows coaches to interface with and communicate with child
30 care providers, (iv) supports child care providers with enrollments via a
31 website and enrollment marketplace, (v) supports the recruitment of teachers
32 for the programs, (vi) provides billing for the programs, (vii) provides ongoing
33 business coaching, and (viii) allows all such technology to be connected and
34 communicate seamlessly.
35 (5) Demonstrated successful experience establishing new family child care homes
36 at scale on time lines of six months or less.
37 SECTION 9M.2.(d) Each vendor selected to participate in the pilot program shall
38 do each of the following:
39 (1) Perform a child care needs analysis to determine where child care providers
40 and substitute teachers are needed.
41 (2) Recruit new potential child care providers and substitutes and plan, staff, and
42 execute in-person and virtual recruitment events for new child care providers
43 in areas of need.
44 (3) Implement technology that meets the requirements of subdivision (c)(4) of
45 this section.
46 (4) Implement technology to operate a substitute teacher pool that matches
47 teachers with providers and facilitates payments and quality control.
48 (5) Develop informational materials that assist in-home family child care
49 providers with marketing, advertising, and parental outreach.
50 (6) Create child care slots and implement a substitute teacher pool available to
51 child care providers in the councils of governments' respective counties.
