20 SUNDAY OPENING STATE HISTORIC SITE PILOT PROGRAM
21 SECTION 14.2.(a) Program Established. – Funds appropriated in this act to the
22 Department of Natural and Cultural Resources (Department) for the Sunday Opening State
23 Historic Site Pilot Program (Program) shall be used by the Department to open and operate the
24 following State Historic Sites on Sundays during each site's peak season:
25 (1) Bentonville Battlefield.
26 (2) Brunswick Town/Fort Anderson.
27 (3) Charlotte Hawkins Brown Museum.
28 (4) Fort Fisher.
29 (5) Governor Charles B. Aycock Birthplace.
30 (6) Historic Bath.
31 (7) Historic Edenton.
32 (8) Historic Halifax.
33 (9) North Carolina State Capitol.
34 (10) Reed Gold Mine.
35 (11) Roanoke Island Festival Park.
36 (12) Somerset Place.
37 (13) Thomas Day State Historic Site.
38 SECTION 14.2.(b) Notice. – The Department shall publish, update, or provide
39 notice of the new operating hours pursuant to the Program established in subsection (a) of this
40 section.
41 SECTION 14.2.(c) Reports. – The Department shall submit the following reports to
42 the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources:
43 (1) By October 1, 2026, an interim report with (i) actual costs by site during the
44 2025-2026 fiscal year, (ii) Sunday visitation numbers by site during the
45 2025-2026 fiscal year, and (iii) preliminary recommendations.
46 (2) By April 1, 2027, an interim report with any funding recommendations the
47 Department has for the upcoming biennium.
48 (3) By October 1, 2027, a final report on the implementation of the Program.
