47 DISPOSITION
48 SECTION 16.16B.(a) Chapter 50 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a
49 new Article to read:
50 "Article 6.
51 "Complex Family Financial Cases.
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 339

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 50-110. Definitions.
2 The following definitions shall apply in this Article:
3 (1) Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge. – A Complex Family Financial
4 Court Judge designated by the Chief Justice of the North Carolina Supreme
5 Court as provided for in G.S. 7A-45.1(a14) who determines which cases are
6 designated as complex family financial cases, assigns all cases designated as
7 complex family financial cases, and prepares any required reports in addition
8 to conducting hearings and entering orders in their assigned complex family
9 financial cases.
10 (2) Complex family financial case. – Any claim or claims approved for hearing
11 as a complex family financial case as provided for by this Article. Claims
12 eligible for hearing as a complex family financial case are equitable
13 distribution, alimony, post separation support, child support, or any
14 combination of those claims.
15 (3) Complex Family Financial Court Judge. – A special superior court judge
16 appointed pursuant to G.S. 7A-45.1(a14) to hear and enter orders in complex
17 family financial cases filed in district court.
18 "§ 50-111. Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
19 To serve as a Complex Family Financial Court Judge, the individual must meet the following
20 minimum qualifications:
21 (1) Attorney licensed in North Carolina and in good standing with the North
22 Carolina State Bar.
23 (2) Substantial involvement handling complex family financial cases during the
24 10 calendar years prior to the year of application, including the following:
25 a. Average at least 600 hours per year handling complex family financial
26 cases.
27 b. No less than 400 hours handling complex family financial cases in any
28 one year.
29 (3) During the five calendar years prior to the application:
30 a. Completed at least 45 hours of continuing legal education credits in
31 family law, nine of which may be in related fields, including taxation,
32 trial advocacy, evidence, negotiation, including training in mediation,
33 arbitration, and collaborative law, real property, estate planning and
34 probate law, trusts, business organizations, employee benefits,
35 bankruptcy, and immigration law. Only nine hours will be recognized
36 for attendance at an extended negotiation or mediation training course.
37 Parenting coordinator training will not qualify for family law or related
38 field hours.
39 b. A minimum of six hours continuing legal education must have been
40 completed in each of those five years.
41 (4) Satisfactory peer review by 10 lawyers or judges who are identified by the
42 applicant. The identified individuals must have personal knowledge of the
43 competence and qualification of the applicant in handling complex family
44 financial matters at the pretrial, trial, and posttrial level. All identified
45 individuals must be licensed and in good standing to practice law in the State
46 of North Carolina. No identified individual may be related by blood or
47 marriage to the applicant nor be a colleague at the applicant's place of
48 employment at the time of the application.
49 "§ 50-112. Authority and duties of a Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
50 (a) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge under this Article has the following
51 authority and responsibilities in all complex family financial cases in district court:
Page 340 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) To conduct hearings and to ensure that the parties' due process rights are
2 protected.
3 (2) To take testimony and establish a record.
4 (3) To evaluate evidence and make decisions regarding the issues being heard.
5 (4) To enter temporary, interim, and final orders related to the issues being heard.
6 (5) To enter orders granting or denying any motion filed under G.S. 1A-1 or any
7 local rules of court for the county in which the action was filed related to
8 actions under this Chapter.
9 (6) To subpoena witnesses and documents.
10 (b) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge is authorized to conduct hearings in district
11 court on complex family financial cases statewide.
12 (c) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge must complete at least nine hours of
13 continuing legal education credits in family law or related fields each year, including taxation,
14 trial advocacy, evidence, negotiation (including training in mediation, arbitration, and
15 collaborative law), real property, estate planning and probate law, trusts, business organizations,
16 employee benefits, bankruptcy, and immigration law. Only one hour per year will be recognized
17 for attendance at negotiation or mediation training, and parenting coordinator training will not
18 qualify for family law or related field hours.
19 "§ 50-113. Designation of a complex family financial claim.
20 (a) A party designating a claim as a complex family financial claim shall file a Notice of
21 Designation in the district court in which the action has been filed and shall contemporaneously
22 serve the notice on all parties or counsel and on the Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
23 The Notice of Designation shall, in good faith and based on information reasonably available,
24 succinctly state each applicable factor provided in G.S. 50-114, the reasons supporting each
25 factor for designation as a complex family financial claim, and any other information supporting
26 designation as a complex family financial claim. Any factor or reasons supporting the designation
27 not asserted shall be deemed conclusively waived.
28 (b) Within 30 days after service of the Notice of Designation, any other party may, in
29 good faith, file and serve an opposition to the designation of the claim as a complex family
30 financial claim. The opposition to the designation of the claim shall assert all reasons for which
31 the party opposing designation objects to the designation, and any reason not asserted shall be
32 deemed conclusively waived. The opposition to the designation shall be served on each opposing
33 party and the Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge and shall be filed in the district court
34 in which the action has been filed.
35 (c) A family court judge assigned to the case may request designation of pending family
36 financial claims as complex family financial claims by following the procedure in subsection (a)
37 of this section. If the judicial district does not have a designated family court, the chief district
38 court judge for the judicial district may request the designation. Any party to the action may file
39 and serve opposition to the request for designation as provided for in subsection (b) of this
40 section.
41 (d) Based on the written Notice of Designation and any opposition filed, the Chief
42 Complex Family Financial Court Judge shall determine whether the action should be designated
43 as a complex family financial claim by written order entered within 45 days of service of the
44 Notice of Designation.
45 (e) Each party shall pay equal shares of the additional filing fee as required under
46 G.S. 7A-305. Only one additional filing fee shall be required per complex family financial case.
47 (f) Once an order granting designation of a claim as a complex family financial claim is
48 entered, that claim shall be designated and administered as a complex family financial case and
49 assigned to a Complex Family Financial Court Judge by the Chief Complex Family Financial
50 Court Judge. All proceedings related to the claims designated as a complex family financial claim
51 shall be before the Complex Family Financial Court Judge to whom the complex family financial
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 341

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 case has been assigned. If any complex family financial claim status is denied, the claim or claims
2 to which the designation was denied shall be heard with any other claims filed under this Chapter.
3 (g) Complex family financial cases are subject to all provisions of Article 1 of this
4 Chapter, the North Carolina Rules of Civil Procedure, the North Carolina Rules of Evidence, any
5 applicable local rules of court for the county in which the complex family financial case is
6 pending, and any rules which may be adopted by the Chief Justice of the North Carolina Supreme
7 Court.
8 "§ 50-114. Factors for complex family financial case determination.
9 The Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge shall consider each of the following factors
10 in determining whether a claim or claims shall be designated as a complex family financial case:
11 (1) Valuation and classification issues related to trusts, including active and
12 passive increases or decreases in value.
13 (2) Valuation and classification issues related to businesses, including active or
14 passive increases or decreases in value.
15 (3) Valuation and classification of real property, including active or passive
16 increases or decreases in value.
17 (4) Valuation and classification issues regarding complex retirement or other
18 employment benefits, including employee stock ownership plans, stock
19 options, profit sharing, defined contribution plans, and defined benefit plans.
20 (5) Valuation and classification of profits, bonuses, or other income or assets
21 received after the date of separation.
22 (6) Active or passive changes in value to separate property during the marriage.
23 (7) Tax issues arising from the distribution of assets and debts, including tax loss
24 carryforwards, refunds, credits, or tax consequences.
25 (8) Whether there are loans or transfers between businesses or shareholders.
26 (9) Whether there are third-party defendants.
27 (10) Validity of a premarital or property settlement agreement pled in defense to
28 an equitable distribution, alimony, post separation support, or child support
29 case.
30 (11) Total value of real and personal property.
31 (12) Calculation of income for spousal support, child support, or both when income
32 includes non W-2 income.
33 (13) Total length of time requested for trial on the issues detailed on the Notice of
34 Designation.
35 Claims which have been filed in excess of 365 days shall be given priority over claims filed
36 less than 365 days, and requested trial dates for the complex family financial case in excess of
37 15 days shall be given priority.
38 "§ 50-115. Complex family financial hearings.
39 (a) Motion hearings shall be held virtually unless the assigned judge determines good
40 cause exists to hold the hearing in person. If an in-person hearing is ordered, it shall be held at
41 the courthouse in the county in which the action was filed in an available district or superior
42 courtroom staffed by a deputy or assistant clerk and bailiff.
43 (b) Hearings on the issues designated as a complex family financial case shall be held in
44 person at the courthouse in the county in which the action was filed in an available district or
45 superior courtroom staffed by a deputy or assistant clerk and bailiff.
46 (c) All complex family financial hearings must be recorded and exhibits maintained as
47 required for any other matter.
48 (d) Any hearing on final disposition of the complex family financial case must be
49 scheduled on consecutive days.
50 "§ 50-116. Appeal from orders of the Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
