6 (a14) In addition to any other special superior court judges authorized by law, effective July
7 1, 2025, the Chief Justice of the North Carolina Supreme Court shall appoint three special
8 superior court judges to serve terms expiring at the earlier of (i) eight years from the date that
9 each judge takes office or (ii) the date of the judge's death, retirement, resignation, or removal
10 from office. Special superior court judges appointed pursuant to this subsection shall be
11 designated as special superior court judges to hear and decide complex family financial cases as
12 defined in G.S. 50-110(2) and shall be known as Complex Family Financial Court Judges.
13 Upon the natural expiration of the term of a special superior court judge appointed pursuant
14 to this subsection, or upon the expiration of a term due to a judge's death, retirement, resignation,
15 or removal from office, a successor shall be appointed to a new term in the same manner and for
16 the same length as other judges appointed pursuant to this subsection.
17 A special superior court judge takes the same oath of office and is subject to the same
18 requirements and disabilities as are or may be prescribed by law for regular judges of the superior
19 court, save the requirement of residence in a particular district and mandatory retirement age.
20 The mandatory retirement age for a special superior court judge appointed pursuant to this
21 subsection shall be 78 years of age.
22 (b) A special judge is subject to removal from office for the same causes and in the same
23 manner as a regular judge of the superior court, and a vacancy occurring in the office of special
24 judge, except as provided for in subsection subsections (a12) and (a14) of this section, is filled
25 by the Governor by appointment for the unexpired term.
26 (c) A special judge, in any court in which he is duly appointed to hold, has the same
27 power and authority in all matters that a regular judge holding the same court would have. A
28 special judge, duly assigned to hold the court of a particular county, has during the session of
29 court in that county, in open court and in chambers, the same power and authority of a regular
30 judge in all matters arising in the district or set of districts as defined in G.S. 7A-41.1(a) in which
31 that county is located, that could properly be heard or determined by a regular judge holding the
32 same session of court.
33 (d) A special judge is authorized to settle cases on appeal and to make all proper orders
34 in regard thereto after the time for which he was commissioned has expired."
