2 MILITARY JUDGES OF THE NORTH CAROLINA NATIONAL GUARD
3 APPOINTMENT MODIFICATIONS
4 SECTION 19.8.(a) G.S. 127A-50 reads as rewritten:
5 "§ 127A-50. Summary courts-martial.
6 (a) In the North Carolina National Guard, not in the service of the United States, summary
7 courts-martial may be appointed by any of the following:
8 (1) Any person who may convene a general or special court-martial.
9 (2) The commander of a battalion, comparable or higher command of the North
10 Carolina Army National Guard, provided that the commander is an officer of
11 the grade of major or above.
12 (3) The commander of a detached squadron, comparable or higher command of
13 the North Carolina Air National Guard, provided that the commander is an
14 officer of the grade of major or above.
15 (b) The court acting under this section shall consist of one officer who shall have the
16 power to administer oaths and try enlisted personnel of each respective command for breaches
17 of discipline and violations of laws governing those organizations. These courts shall also have
18 the power to impose punishments in like manner and to the extent prescribed by the Uniform
19 Code of Military Justice and Manual for Courts-Martial, United States, as shall be in use by the
20 Armed Forces of the United States at the time of the offense, except that no officer, the State
21 military judge, and a judge advocate detailed to the court as a hearing officer. A summary
22 court-martial shall have the authority to impose fines of not more than five hundred dollars
23 ($500.00), to impose forfeitures of two-thirds pay for one month, to restrict to limits, to impose
24 extra duty, and to reduce the rank of enlisted persons E7 and above by up to two ranks and
25 enlisted persons E6 and below to the rank of E1.
26 (c) No court acting under this section shall have the authority to impose confinement as
27 part of a sentence.
28 (d) There shall be no right during summary courts-martial to demand trial by
29 court-martial."
30 SECTION 19.8.(b) G.S. 127A-50.1 reads as rewritten:
31 "§ 127A-50.1. Military judges.
32 The Adjutant General shall appoint military judges to preside over courts-martial of the North
33 Carolina National Guard not in federal service. Minimum requirements for appointment as a
34 military judge are:are the following:
35 (1) Certification as a military judge by the Judge Advocate General of the United
36 States Army, Air Force, Navy, Marines, or Coast Guard.
37 (2) Designation as a judge advocate by the Judge Advocate General of the United
38 States Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines, or Coast Guard.
39 (3) Membership in the North Carolina National Guard, the National Guard of
40 another state, or the active or reserve components of the Armed Forces of the
41 United States.
42 (4) A member in good standing for at least 10 years of either of the following:
43 a. The bar of the highest court of this State or any other state.
44 b. The bar of a federal court.
45 (5) Hold the rank of lieutenant colonel or above."
46 SECTION 19.8.(c) Subsection (a) of this section is effective when it becomes law
47 and applies to summary courts-martial initiated on or after that date. Subsection (b) of this section
48 is effective when it becomes law and applies to military judges serving on or after that date,
49 except the requirements of G.S. 127A-50.1, as amended by subsection (b) of this section, shall
50 only apply to appointments made on or after that date. The remainder of this section is effective
51 when it becomes law.
