1 a. Parent-child interaction therapy.
2 b. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
3 c. Behavioral therapy.
4 d. Dialectical behavior therapy.
5 e. Child-parent psychotherapy.
6 (3) Training for students and school employees on community resilience models
7 to models, violence prevention, and developing personal and interpersonal
8 skills to (i) enhance individual level protective factors, (ii) mitigate or reduce
9 risk taking or harmful behavior, and (iii) improve understanding and responses
10 to trauma and significant stress.
11 (4) Training for school health support personnel on Modular Approach to
12 Therapy for Children with Anxiety, Depression, Trauma, or Conduct
13 problems (MATCH-ADTC), including any of the following components:
14 a. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
15 b. Parent and student coping skills.
16 c. Problem solving.
17 d. Safety planning.
18 (5) Any other training, including the training on the facilitation of peer-to-peer
19 mentoring, training or education programming that is likely to increase school
20 safety. The training or education programming authorized in this subdivision
21 includes training on the facilitation of peer-to-peer mentoring, education on
22 personal and interpersonal skills or character education, and education or
23 training addressing violence prevention and suicide prevention. Of the funds
24 appropriated by this act for the grants provided in this section, the Executive
25 Director shall use no more than three hundred fifty thousand dollars
26 ($350,000) in the 2024-2025 fiscal year for the services identified in this
27 subdivision."
28 SECTION 20.7.(b) Definitions. – For the purposes of subsections (b) through (m)
29 of this section, the following definitions shall apply:
30 (1) Community partner. – A public or private entity, including, but not limited to,
31 a nonprofit corporation or a local management entity/managed care
32 organization (LME/MCO), that partners with a public school unit to provide
33 services or pay for the provision of services for the unit.
34 (2) School health support personnel. – School psychologists, school counselors,
35 school nurses, and school social workers.
36 SECTION 20.7.(c) Program; Purpose. – The Executive Director of the Center for
37 Safer Schools shall establish the School Safety Grants Program (Program) for the 2025-2027
38 fiscal biennium. The purpose of the Program shall be to improve safety in public school units by
39 providing grants in each fiscal year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for (i) services for students
40 in crisis, (ii) school safety training, (iii) safety equipment in schools, and (iv) subsidizing the
41 School Resource Officer Grants Program.
42 SECTION 20.7.(d) Grant Applications. – A public school unit may submit an
43 application to the Executive Director of the Center for Safer Schools for one or more grants
44 pursuant to this section in each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. The application shall
45 include an assessment, to be performed in conjunction with a local law enforcement agency, of
46 the need for improving school safety within the public school unit that would receive the funding
47 or services. The application shall identify current and ongoing needs and estimated costs
48 associated with those needs.
49 SECTION 20.7.(e) Criteria and Guidelines. – The Executive Director of the Center
50 for Safer Schools shall develop criteria and guidelines for the administration and use of the grants
51 pursuant to this section, including any documentation required to be submitted by applicants. In
Page 376 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 assessing grant applications, the Executive Director shall consider at least all of the following
2 factors:
3 (1) The level of resources available to the public school unit that would receive
4 the funding.
5 (2) Whether the public school unit has received other grants for school safety.
6 (3) The overall impact on student safety in the public school unit if the identified
7 needs are funded.
8 SECTION 20.7.(f) Grants for Students in Crisis. – Of the funds appropriated by this
9 act for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director of the Center for Safer Schools,
10 in consultation with the Department of Health and Human Services, shall award grants to public
11 school units to contract with community partners to provide or pay for the provision of any of
12 the following crisis services:
13 (1) Crisis respite services for parents or guardians of an individual student to
14 prevent more intensive or costly levels of care.
15 (2) Training and expanded services for therapeutic foster care families and
16 licensed child placement agencies that provide services to students who (i)
17 need support to manage their health, welfare, and safety and (ii) have any of
18 the following:
19 a. Cognitive or behavioral problems.
20 b. Developmental delays.
21 c. Aggressive behavior.
22 (3) Evidence-based therapy services aligned with targeted training for students
23 and their parents or guardians, including any of the following:
24 a. Parent-child interaction therapy.
25 b. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
26 c. Dialectical behavior therapy.
27 d. Child-parent psychotherapy.
28 (4) Any other crisis service, including peer-to-peer mentoring, that is likely to
29 increase school safety. Of the funds appropriated by this act for the grants
30 provided in this section, the Executive Director shall use no more than three
31 hundred fifty thousand dollars ($350,000) in each fiscal year of the 2025-2027
32 fiscal biennium for the services identified in this subdivision.
