43 SECTION 27.2.(a) G.S. 66-58.12 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 66-58.12. Agencies may provide access to services through electronic and digital
45 transactions; fees authorized.
46 (a) Public agencies are encouraged to maximize citizen and business access to their
47 services through the use of electronic and digital transactions. A public agency may determine,
48 through program and transaction analysis, which of its services may be made available to the
49 public through electronic means, including the Internet. The agency shall identify any inhibitors
50 to electronic transactions between the agency and the public, including legal, policy, financial,
51 or privacy concerns and specific inhibitors unique to the agency or type of transaction. An agency
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 397

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall not provide a transaction through the Internet that is impractical, unreasonable, or not
2 permitted by laws pertaining to privacy or security.
3 (b) An agency may charge a fee to cover its costs of permitting a person to complete a
4 transaction through the World Wide Web internet or other means of electronic access. The
5 transaction fee may be applied on a per transaction basis and may be calculated either as a flat
6 fee or a percentage fee, as determined under an agreement between a person and a public agency.
7 The fee may be collected by the agency or by its third party agent.fee. Neither the flat fee nor the
8 percentage fee shall exceed two percent (2%) of the total amount of each transaction. An agency
9 shall not charge a surcharge for accepting electronic payments. For purposes of this subsection,
10 the following definitions apply:
11 (1) Surcharge. – A fee added to a payment by charge card, credit card, debit card,
12 or by electronic funds transfer for the convenience of making the electronic
13 payment or for any other purpose not authorized by law.
14 (2) Transaction fee. – A fee charged by a payment processor to a State agency for
15 processing a charge card, credit card, or debit card payment.
16 (c) The fee flat fee or percentage fee imposed under subsection (b) of this section must
17 be approved by the State Chief Information Officer. The revenue derived from the fee must be
18 credited to a nonreverting agency reserve account. The funds in the account may be expended
19 only for e-commerce initiatives and projects approved by the State Chief Information Officer.
20 For purposes of this subsection, the term "public agencies" does not include a county, unit, special
21 district, or other political subdivision of government. The State Chief Information Officer shall
22 report any fees imposed under subsection (b) of this section and expenditures for e-commerce
23 initiatives and projects to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and the
24 Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Information Technology.
25 (d) This section does not apply to the Judicial Department."
