23 when fund reaches five percent of total insurance in force.Fund.
24 (a) There is established a Creation. – The State Public Education Property Insurance Fund
25 (Fund) is established as a nonreverting special fund in the State treasury for the purpose of
26 providing a reserve against property loss of public education boards. The State Treasurer shall
27 be the custodian of the Fund and shall invest its assets in accordance with the provisions of
28 G.S. 147-69.2 and G.S. 147-69.3. All funds paid over to the State Treasurer by the State Fire
29 Marshal for premiums on insurance by public education boards and all money received from
30 interest or from loans and deposits and from any other source connected with the insurance of
31 the property shall be held by the State Treasurer in the Fund for the purpose of paying all
32 insurable hazards for which the Fund shall be liable and the expenses necessary for the proper
33 conduct of the insurance of such property, together with such premiums for reinsurance that the
34 State Fire Marshal may deem necessary to reinsure as provided by this Article.Department of
35 Insurance.
36 (b) When the balance of the Fund reaches the sum of five percent (5%) of the total
37 insurance in force, then annually thereafter the State Fire Marshal shall proportionately decrease
38 the premiums on insurance to an amount which will be sufficient to maintain the Fund at five
39 percent (5%) of the total insurance in force, and in the event in the judgment of the State Fire
40 Marshal the income from the investments of the Fund are sufficient to maintain the same at five
41 percent (5%) of the total insurance in force, no premium shall be charged for the ensuing year.
42 However, no public education board shall cease to pay premiums until five annual payments of
43 premiums have been made on a building or property insured whether or not through such
44 payments the Fund shall be increased beyond five percent (5%) of the total insurance in force,
45 unless such building or property shall cease to be insurable under this Article within such
46 five-year period.
