8 USE OF CAPITAL FUNDS ON SUSTAINABILITY ELEMENTS
9 SECTION 42.9.(a) G.S. 143C-8-7.1 reads as rewritten:
10 "§ 143C-8-7.1. Procedures for disbursement of capital funds.
11 (a) Appropriations made by an act of the General Assembly for capital improvements are
12 for constructing, repairing, or renovating State buildings, utilities, and other capital facilities; for
13 acquiring sites for them where necessary; for acquiring buildings and land for State government
14 purposes and other purposes as set forth in G.S. 143C-4-3.1; and shall be disbursed for the
15 purposes provided by that act. Expenditure of funds shall not be made by any State department,
16 institution, or agency until an allotment has been issued by the Governor as Director of the
17 Budget, which shall not be unreasonably withheld. The allotment shall be issued upon
18 compliance with the provisions of this Chapter. Prior to the award of construction contracts for
19 projects to be financed in whole or in part with self-liquidating appropriations, the Director of
20 the Budget shall approve the elements of the method of financing of those projects, including the
21 source of funds, interest rate, and liquidation period. Provided, however, that if the Director of
22 the Budget approves the method of financing a project, the Director shall report that action to the
23 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations within 30 days.
24 (b) Where direct capital improvement appropriations include the purpose of furnishing
25 fixed and movable equipment for any project, those funds for equipment shall not be subject to
26 transfer into construction accounts except as authorized by the Director of the Budget. The
27 expenditure of funds for fixed and movable equipment and furnishings shall be reviewed and
28 approved by the Director of the Budget prior to commitment of funds.
29 (c) Capital improvement projects authorized by an act of the General Assembly shall be
30 completed, including fixed and movable equipment and furnishings, within the limits of the
31 amounts of the direct or self-liquidating appropriations provided, except as otherwise provided
32 in that act. Capital improvement projects authorized by an act of the General Assembly for the
33 design phase only shall be designed within the scope of the project as defined by the approved
34 cost estimate filed with the Director of the Budget, including costs associated with site
35 preparation, demolition, and movable and fixed equipment. Amounts contracted for projects
36 authorized by the General Assembly cannot exceed the total project cost authorization.
37 (d) Disbursement of funds from the State Capital and Infrastructure Fund for projects
38 authorized by an act of the General Assembly shall be made as needed to initiate or advance a
39 capital project. Funds authorized for any particular project shall remain in the State Capital and
40 Infrastructure Fund until such time as disbursement is necessary to satisfy a financial obligation
41 for that project.
42 (e) Funds disbursed for capital improvement projects may not be used for certification
43 under Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED), Green Globes, Living Building
44 Challenge, or other similar environmental or sustainability certification or rating by an equivalent
45 or greater, nationally recognized certification or rating system, unless the estimated operating
46 costs for the first 10 years post-construction would be less than the cost of construction or
47 renovation if the project were not subject to the requirements of this section plus the estimated
48 operating costs for the first 10 years post-construction. All third-party certification costs before
49 and after construction or renovation shall be included in determining construction and operating
50 costs."
