6 USE OF CAPITAL FUNDS FOR PUBLIC-PRIVATE PARTNERSHIPS
7 SECTION 42.10. G.S. 143C-8-7.1 reads as rewritten:
8 "§ 143C-8-7.1. Procedures for disbursement of capital funds.
9 (a) Appropriations made by an act of the General Assembly for capital improvements are
10 for constructing, repairing, or renovating State buildings, utilities, and other capital facilities; for
11 acquiring sites for them where necessary; for acquiring buildings and land for State government
12 purposes and other purposes as set forth in G.S. 143C-4-3.1; and shall be disbursed for the
13 purposes provided by that act. Expenditure of funds shall not be made by any State department,
14 institution, or agency until an allotment has been issued by the Governor as Director of the
15 Budget, which shall not be unreasonably withheld. The allotment shall be issued upon
16 compliance with the provisions of this Chapter. Prior to the award of construction contracts for
17 projects to be financed in whole or in part with self-liquidating appropriations, the Director of
18 the Budget shall approve the elements of the method of financing of those projects, including the
19 source of funds, interest rate, and liquidation period. Provided, however, that if the Director of
20 the Budget approves the method of financing a project, the Director shall report that action to the
21 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations within 30 days.
22 (a1) State funds appropriated for a capital improvement project at a State agency that is
23 not a public-private partnership project shall not be used in conjunction with or for the benefit of
24 a public-private partnership project without express authorization by an act of the General
25 Assembly. For the purposes of this subsection, the term "public-private partnership" means a
26 capital improvement project undertaken for the benefit of a governmental entity and a private
27 entity that may involve a contract, a financing arrangement, or other agreement, and includes
28 construction of a public facility or other improvements, including paving, grading, utilities,
29 infrastructure, reconstruction, or repair, and may include both public and private facilities.
30 (b) Where direct capital improvement appropriations include the purpose of furnishing
31 fixed and movable equipment for any project, those funds for equipment shall not be subject to
32 transfer into construction accounts except as authorized by the Director of the Budget. The
33 expenditure of funds for fixed and movable equipment and furnishings shall be reviewed and
34 approved by the Director of the Budget prior to commitment of funds.
35 (c) Capital improvement projects authorized by an act of the General Assembly shall be
36 completed, including fixed and movable equipment and furnishings, within the limits of the
37 amounts of the direct or self-liquidating appropriations provided, except as otherwise provided
38 in that act. Capital improvement projects authorized by an act of the General Assembly for the
39 design phase only shall be designed within the scope of the project as defined by the approved
40 cost estimate filed with the Director of the Budget, including costs associated with site
41 preparation, demolition, and movable and fixed equipment. Amounts contracted for projects
42 authorized by the General Assembly cannot exceed the total project cost authorization.
43 (d) Disbursement of funds from the State Capital and Infrastructure Fund for projects
44 authorized by an act of the General Assembly shall be made as needed to initiate or advance a
45 capital project. Funds authorized for any particular project shall remain in the State Capital and
46 Infrastructure Fund until such time as disbursement is necessary to satisfy a financial obligation
47 for that project."
