33 PILOT PROGRAM TO ALLOW COMMERCIAL DRIVER TRAINING SCHOOLS TO
34 ADMINISTER EXAMINATIONS REQUIRED FOR DRIVERS LICENSING
35 SECTION 43.19.(a) The Division of Motor Vehicles shall develop a pilot program
36 to authorize commercial driver training schools licensed under Article 14 of Chapter 20 of the
37 General Statutes to additionally administer all examinations required for drivers licensing and
38 permitting in accordance with G.S. 20-7, 20-11, and 20-37.13. The Division's plan for
39 implementation of the pilot program shall include all of the following:
40 (1) The Division shall select at least two but not more than five counties in diverse
41 geographic regions in which to implement the pilot program.
42 (2) Commercial driver training schools must offer the same examinations as those
43 administered by the Division, using the same scoring methods and standards,
44 and must administer examinations in compliance with all applicable State and
45 federal requirements.
46 (3) Examinations may be offered by participating commercial driver training
47 schools outside of standard Division office hours on any day of the week.
48 (4) The Division shall develop a process for a prospective licensee to demonstrate
49 successful completion of an examination administered by a commercial driver
50 training school, whereby documentation may be provided to the prospective
Page 520 Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 licensee or submitted directly to the Division by the school administering the
2 examination.
3 (5) Upon successful completion of examinations required for licensing or
4 permitting administered by a commercial driver training school in accordance
5 with the pilot program established by the Division, a prospective licensee must
6 appear in person at a Division office to be photographed and present required
7 documentation. The Division shall update its appointment system to provide
8 appropriate appointment availability for purposes of the pilot program.
9 (6) For each type of drivers licensing – graduated, regular drivers, and
10 commercial drivers – the Division shall develop a plan for informing
11 prospective licensees about required examinations that will be administered
12 by commercial driver training schools through the pilot program.
13 (7) The Division shall maintain complete oversight over administration of
14 examinations by commercial driver training schools participating in the pilot
15 program, including providing schools with training, guidelines, and materials
16 required to administer examinations in accordance with Division standards.
17 (8) The Division must take prompt and appropriate remedial action against any
18 participating commercial driver training school that fails to comply with
19 Division standards or applicable State and federal requirements.
20 SECTION 43.19.(b) The Division shall report its plan for implementation of the
21 pilot program outlined in subsection (a) of this section to the Joint Legislative Transportation
22 Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division no later than April 1, 2026. The report
23 shall include an examination of the anticipated costs of implementing the pilot program, the
24 number of anticipated participating licensed commercial driver training schools in selected
25 counties, and any recommendations or legislative proposals related to the proposed pilot
26 program.
27 SECTION 43.19.(c) Nothing in this section shall limit any authorization set forth in
28 Article 14 of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes.
29 SECTION 43.19.(d) The Division shall implement the pilot program on January 1,
30 2027. No later than January 1, 2029, the Division shall submit a report to the Joint Legislative
31 Transportation Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division evaluating the
32 effectiveness of the pilot program in improving the drivers licensing process and any
33 recommendations related to extending, expanding, or terminating the program. The pilot program
34 shall terminate on July 1, 2029.
