34 UNIT PRICING COST
35 SECTION 43.22. G.S. 136-18.05(b)(1a) reads as rewritten:
36 "(1a) Efficiency. – The Department shall adopt procedures in all stages of the
37 construction process to streamline project delivery, including consolidating
38 environmental review processes, expediting multiagency reviews,
39 accelerating right-of-way acquisitions, and pursuing design build and other
40 processes to collapse project stages. By December 1, 2015, the Department
41 shall establish a baseline unit pricing structure for transportation goods used
42 in highway maintenance and construction projects and set annual targets for
43 three years based on its unit pricing. In forming the baseline unit prices and
44 future targets, the Department shall collect data from each Highway Division
45 on its expenditures on transportation goods during the 2015-2016 fiscal year.
46 based upon a rolling average of the three previous fiscal years. Beginning
47 January 1, 2016, no Highway Division shall exceed a ten percent (10%)
48 variance over a baseline unit price set for that year in accordance with this
49 subdivision. The Department of Transportation shall institute annual tracking
50 to monitor pricing variances. The ten percent (10%) maximum variance set
51 under this subdivision is intended to account for regional differences requiring
Senate Bill 257-Sixth Edition Page 523

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 varying product mixes. If a Highway Division exceeds the unit pricing
2 threshold, the Department shall submit a report to the Joint Legislative
3 Transportation Oversight Committee, the Fiscal Research Division of the
4 General Assembly, the chairs of the House of Representatives Appropriations
5 Committee on Transportation, and the chairs of the Senate Appropriations
6 Committee on the Department of Transportation no later than the fifteenth day
7 of February following the end of the calendar year on why the variance
8 occurred and what steps are being taken to bring the Highway Division back
9 into compliance. In order to drive savings, unit pricing may be reduced
10 annually as efficiencies are achieved."
